   "source": [
    "# qdisc\n",
    "\n",
    "> "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<p align=\"center\">\n",
    "  <img width=\"250\" src=\"nbs/figs/VAE4Spins_logo.png/">\n",
    "</p>\n",
    "<h3 align=\"center\"><em>Interpretable Machine Learning • Scientific Discovery • Quantum Physics</em></h3>\n",
    "<p align=\"center\">\n",
    "  <a href=\"https://badge.fury.io/py/projective_simulation\"><img src=\"https://badge.fury.io/py/projective_simulation.svg\" alt=\"PyPI version\"></a>\n",
    "  <a href=\"https://badge.fury.io/py/projective_simulation\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/badge/python-3.10-red\" alt=\"Python version\"></a>\n",
    "</p>\n",
    "<p align=\"center\">\n",
    "  <a href=\"https://qic-ibk.github.io/projective_simulation/\">Get started</a> |\n",
    "  <a href=\"https://qic-ibk.github.io/projective_simulation/lib_nbs/index_docs.html\">Documentation</a> |\n",
    "  <a href=\"https://qic-ibk.github.io/projective_simulation/tutorials/index_tutorials.html\">Tutorials</a> \n",
    "</p>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**QDisc** is a library for discovering and interpreting quantum phases directly from raw quantum data, such as measurements obtained in quantum experiments. It focuses on interpretable machine learning methods that uncover emergent structure without requiring labeled data or prior knowledge of the phase diagram.\n",
    "\n",
    "The library provides end-to-end tools to learn a low-dimensional representation of the phase space from raw inputs. At its core, QDisc employs a variational autoencoder (**VAE**) trained to reconstruct conditional probabilities of the input data. The resulting latent representation naturally aligns with the underlying structure of the phase space and can reveal previously unknown phases or clusters.\n",
    "\n",
    "To interpret the physical meaning of the structures uncovered in latent space, QDisc integrates symbolic regression methods (**SR**). These methods search for compact analytic expressions that characterize the identified clusters, enabling the extraction of interpretable order parameters and effective physical descriptors directly from the learned representation.\n",
    "\n",
    "The complete discovery pipeline is summarized below."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "> **Automated Phase Discovery Pipeline**\n",
    ">\n",
    "> **Setup:** Quantum system tunable by parameters  \n",
    "> $\\{\\theta_1, \\dots, \\theta_k\\}$\n",
    ">\n",
    "> 1. Collect quantum data $\\vec{x}$ for a wide range of parameter values  \n",
    ">    *Snapshots, classical shadows, densities, etc.*\n",
    "> 2. Train a VAE on the unlabeled dataset such that it reconstructs the conditional probabilities (cpVAE)\n",
    "> 3. Identify active latent variables $z$  \n",
    ">    *Select latent neurons with small variance $\\sigma$*\n",
    "> 4. Visualize the latent representation across the parameter space  \n",
    ">    *Reveal phase structure and emergent clusters*\n",
    "> 5. If unknown clusters are appearing:\n",
    ">    - Apply symbolic regression to the latent representation  \n",
    ">    - Extract compact analytic expressions  \n",
    ">      *Interpret as candidate order parameters*\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Getting Started"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To begin using the library, we recommend starting with the two [tutorials](tutorials) notebooks. These tutorials provide a step-by-step introduction to the core tools and workflows, using a simple toy example: the $J_1$–$J_2$ model on a square lattice.\n",
    "\n",
    "Additional [examples](examples) notebooks (TODO: add links) are also available and cover a variety of quantum data types, including:\n",
    "- Measurement snapshots of Rydberg atom systems\n",
    "- Classical shadows of the cluster Ising model\n",
    "- Hybrid data from a fermionic system\n",
    "\n",
    "These examples reproduce the results presented in the accompanying paper (TODO: add reference)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Developer Guide"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "If you are new to using `nbdev` here are some useful pointers to get you started."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Install qdisc in Development mode"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "```sh\n",
    "# make sure qdisc package is installed in development mode\n",
    "$ pip install -e .\n",
    "\n",
    "# make changes under nbs/ directory\n",
    "# ...\n",
    "\n",
    "# compile to have changes apply to qdisc\n",
    "$ nbdev_prepare\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Usage"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Installation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Install latest from the GitHub [repository][repo]:\n",
    "\n",
    "```sh\n",
    "$ pip install git+https://github.com/PaulinDS/qdisc.git\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "or from [conda][conda]\n",
    "\n",
    "```sh\n",
    "$ conda install -c PaulinDS qdisc\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "or from [pypi][pypi]\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "```sh\n",
    "$ pip install qdisc\n",
    "```\n",
